LinkedHashSet is a Set implementation in Java that stores unique elements AND maintains insertion order.

So it means:

No duplicates
Maintains order of insertion
DataStructures used internally by HashMap + Linked List


LinkedHashSet = HashMap (for uniqueness + hashing)
              + Doubly Linked List (for order)

Each node contains:
[prev | hash | key | value | next]

LinkedHashSet behavior:
Still uses HashMap collision handling
BUT order is preserved via linked list

Why LinkedHashSet is slower than HashSet?

Because it does extra work:

Maintains doubly linked list
Updates next & prev pointers on every insert/remove
Extra memory per node

HashSet → only HashMap → faster
LinkedHashSet → HashMap + LinkedList → slightly slower


